  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Here are some key examples:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention):** This is one of the earliest international treaties to address money laundering, specifically related to drug trafficking. It requires countries to criminalize the laundering of drug money.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention):** This convention expands the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug-related crimes to include the proceeds of other serious crimes. It also promotes international cooperation in investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003 Merida Convention):** This convention focuses on combating corruption and includes provisions on preventing and combating money laundering related to corruption offenses.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** While not a treaty, the FATF Recommendations are the global standard for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction. Over 200 countries and jurisdictions have committed to implementing these recommendations. The FATF is an inter-governmental body established in 1989 by the Ministers of its Member jurisdictions. The objectives of the FATF are to set standards and promote effective implementation of legal, regulatory and operational measures for combating money laundering, terrorist financing and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime and on the Financing of Terrorism (CETS No. 198):** This convention provides a comprehensive framework for combating money laundering and terrorist financing in Europe and beyond. It covers a wide range of measures, including criminalization of money laundering, confiscation of proceeds of crime, and international cooperation.\n\nThese are just some of the key international laws and conventions that address money laundering. Many countries also have their own domestic laws to combat money laundering, which are often based on these international standards.",
